Stanchion Use Policy
Purpose:  
Always remember that safety comes first. Using stanchions or barriers to cordon off your work area and identify 
potential hazards is crucial. By doing so, you’re not only preventing unauthorized access but also protecting 
yourself, colleagues, customers, and patrons from harm. Remember, safety is not just a priority; it’s a value we 
should embody in everything we do.
Responsibilities: 
It is the responsibility of the first technician on the project to set up stanchions or barriers, cordon off the work 
area, and ensure adequate protection. However, everyone in the work area is responsible for following the safety 
procedures outlined in this document. If you will be moving games in and out of the casino you should plan your 
route and be sure that it is clear of obstructions. See if Security or Facility employees are able to assist in opening 
and closing doors, and keeping the route clear of patrons. If the casino supplies and sets up the stanchions, it is 
still the GCG tech’s responsibility to make sure setup is done properly and safely in accordance with this policy. If 
the property does not allow you to rearrange the stanchions as needed, then you should notify your manager and 
make them aware of the situation.
Procedures: 
• The work area should be cordoned off at the beginning of the project before starting any work. This includes 
properties that are currently closed and will open later in the day.
• Select the appropriate type of stanchion or barrier for the job. If the casino can supply stanchions, use them. 
If not, then use your magnetic barriers. If that’s not possible then caution tape should be used to mark off the 
area.  
• Set up the stanchions or barriers in a way that clearly defines the boundaries of your work area. 
• Use 2 stand up stanchions to define an entry and exit point (gate) into the work area. Make sure everyone in 
the work area is aware of the gate and they use it and close it behind them.
• Stanchions should be spaced evenly and enough stanchions should be used to prevent over stretching and 
causing the base to tip  over. Magnetic barriers and/or caution tape should be placed high enough so that it’s 
easily visible, approximately 36” (waist height) off the floor.
• Secure the stanchions or barriers so that they do not move or are easily knocked down. 
• Place caution tape around the stanchions if needed to further warn people to stay away. 
• Monitor the work area regularly to ensure that the stanchions and magnetic barriers are in good condition, 
that the work area is still adequately protected, and that nothing has been pushed or fallen outside the 
protected area. 
• Be aware of other vendors and try to avoid blocking off their machines. If it is necessary, try getting their 
area cleared outside your work zone ASAP.  
• Tools, equipment, dollies, boxes, and any other items not needed for the project should be removed from the 
work area and taken to the box truck.
Hazards: 
• People may ignore the stanchions and enter the work area. Always check your work area. 
• Stanchions may get knocked over and people may trip over them, causing possible injury.
• Caution tape that is not secured well may come loose, posing a tripping hazard.
• Hardware and tools outside the cordoned work area may be a tripping hazard.
• Technicians working in the cordoned area should be aware of their legs and feet and avoid extending them 
outside the cordoned-off area. This will help to prevent people from tripping over you.
 By following these safety procedures, you can help to ensure  
 the safety of workers and the public to prevent accidents and injuries. 
By signing below, I acknowledge that I have been trained and understand GCG’s Stanchion Use 
Policy. I agree to abide by this policy at all times and understand that any violation of GCG’s Stanchion 
Use Policy may result in disciplinary action, up to and including termination of employment.
